name: Cloud-forest Screech-Owl
rangeDescription: Cloud forest of east slope of andes from central peru (pasco) southward to central bolivia (cochabamba)
description: Small screech-owl known from relatively few sites along the east slope of the Andes from central Peru to Bolivia. The bold dark crescents that border its buffy facial disks separate it from Rufescent Screech-Owl and Cinnamon Screech-Owl.

name: Juba Weaver
rangeDescription: Riparian vegetation of southeastern ethiopia, juba region of southern somalia, and northeastern kenya
description: A fairly small, compact weaver with a large bill. Breeding males are colorful, with a black head, a red eye, a rufous chest, and a yellow belly and back.

name: Masked Duck
rangeDescription: Northeastern mexico and caribbean southward to south america; west of the andes to western ecuador, and east of the andes to northern argentina and brazil
description: Reclusive, rarely seen diving duck of tropical lowlands. Feeds mainly at night and spends much of the day sleeping quietly in marshy vegetation, often in small ponds and even in roadside ditches.

name: Pink-footed Shearwater
rangeDescription: Mocha and juan fernández islands off chile; ranges to north pacific
description: Large shearwater, often messy-looking with smudgy brown neck and underwings. Underparts are usually fairly clean white, but sometimes mottled brownish or rarely all-dark.

name: Gray-chinned Sunbird
rangeDescription: Southeastern benin and southern nigeria eastward to southern central african republic, southern south sudan, uganda, southwestern kenya, and northwestern tanzania, southward to northern angola and southern democratic republic of the congo; bioko
description: A very small sunbird with a short, slightly curved bill. Males are iridescent leaf green above with a red-and-black chest band, a gray throat, and a buffy gray belly.

name: Black-headed Shrike-Babbler
rangeDescription: Nepal to bhutan, assam, northern myanmar, sichuan, northwestern yunnan, and northwestern vietnam (fansipan mountain)
description: Large-headed songbird with confusingly dissimilar male and female plumages. Male has an orange back, white throat, orangish belly, and a black head and wings.

name: Tambourine Dove
rangeDescription: Sub-saharan africa, bioko, and comoros
description: Small dove with a dark brown back and pale face and underparts. In flight, the wings show rufous patches.

name: Rufous-faced Antbird
rangeDescription: Brazil south of the amazon river (rio madeira to rio tocantins, and northern rondônia)
description: Medium-sized, chunky, rather drab antbird. Males are uniform gray with white spots on the wing-coverts and females are rusty below with darker backs.

name: Jameson's Snipe
rangeDescription: Andes of colombia to western venezuela and eastern bolivia
description: Chunky snipe of very high elevations in the Andes. Plumage has a complicated pattern of brown, buff, and black; note extensive barring on underparts and thick, drooping bill.

name: Yungas Manakin
rangeDescription: Southeastern peru (cusco, southern madre de dios, and puno) and western bolivia
description: Fairly large manakin of montane forest habitats. Males are black with a blue back and red cap; females are dull olive green.

name: Gray-headed Piprites
rangeDescription: Caribbean lowlands of eastern guatemala to costa rica
description: Confusing forest species, rare and difficult to find among mixed flocks. Typically stays at middle levels.

name: Ochraceous Attila
rangeDescription: Far southwestern colombia to western ecuador and northwestern peru (tumbes)
description: Bright, tawny flycatcher with a hooked bill. Nearly endemic to western Ecuador, just barely reaching Peru and Colombia.

name: White-winged Warbler
rangeDescription: Montane forest of hispaniola
description: A denizen of mature montane forests wherein it feeds low in thickets and shrubs. Often found in pairs, but sometimes in mixed feeding flocks.

name: Nava's Wren
rangeDescription: Lowlands of southern mexico (chiapas and far eastern veracruz)
description: Very local in humid evergreen forest of limestone (karst) lowlands and foothills in southernmost Veracruz and adjacent Chiapas; endemic. Stays on or near the ground, moving quickly over and among limestone boulders, popping in and out of caves and crevices.

name: Yellow-crowned Flowerpecker
rangeDescription: Northern philippines (montane forest of luzon)
description: A tiny bird of mossy montane forest and edge on Luzon. Male has glossy black upperparts, pale underparts (whiter on the throat), and the namesake yellow crown stripe.

name: Sokoke Pipit
rangeDescription: Coastal forest of southeastern kenya and northeastern tanzania
description: A rare small pipit found in a limited region of the East African coast, where it is very local in coastal forest. Rich rufous-brown above and white below with bold streaking on the breast.
imageCreditName: Lars Petersson | My World of Bird Photography

name: Western Kingbird
rangeDescription: Breeds western north america; winters southern mexico to costa rica and (?) panama
description: Fairly large yellow-bellied flycatcher; common and widespread in western North America. Rather pale gray head with weakly contrasting whitish throat and breast, and lemon-yellow belly.

name: Plain Swift
rangeDescription: Madeira and western canary islands; winters in northern africa
description: Medium-sized swift, very similar to Common Swift, but is noticeably paler, especially against a dark background. Wings are narrower and very pointed and the tail is longer and more deeply forked than Common or Pallid Swifts.

name: Alder Flycatcher
rangeDescription: Breeds alaska to northeastern usa; winters colombia to bolivia
description: Small flycatcher, extremely similar to several other species. Prefers clearings and boggy areas, often with patches of alders.

name: Lazuli Bunting
rangeDescription: Southern british columbia to northwestern baja california and western texas; winters in mexico
description: Breeding males are unmistakable: bright cerulean above with bold white wingbars, white belly, and orange breast. Females are plain buffy brown with paler wingbars and slightly brighter orangey breast.
